#Great plan. Use a stable prefix from what you know (day/agent/summaryType) and append a short, collision-safe random suffix.

Recommended ID shape

<yyyyMMdd>=<agentId>=<summaryType>=<rand20>

	•	If any part is unknown, put "_" (or "unknown").
	•	Keep only URL/table-safe chars. Avoid / \ ? # % etc. (“=” is OK for Cosmos DB docs.)

Short, safe random suffix

Use 100–128 bits from SecureRandom, Base32-Crockford (letters+digits, uppercase, no symbols).
20 chars gives ~100 bits; collisions are effectively zero for your scale.

Java helper

import java.security.SecureRandom;
import java.time.LocalDate;
import java.time.ZoneId;
import java.util.Objects;

public final class CorrelationIds {
  private static final SecureRandom RNG = new SecureRandom();
  private static final char[] B32 = "0123456789ABCDEFGHJKMNPQRSTVWXYZ".toCharArray(); // Crockford

  /** 100-bit random, Base32 Crockford -> 20 chars */
  public static String rand20() {
    byte[] bytes = new byte[13]; // 104 bits
    RNG.nextBytes(bytes);
    return base32(bytes);
  }

  /** Build: yyyyMMdd=agentId=summaryType=rand20 ; use "_" for missing parts. */
  public static String build(String yyyyMMdd, String agentId, String summaryType) {
    String d = safe(yyyyMMdd);
    String a = safe(agentId);
    String s = safe(summaryType);
    return d + "=" + a + "=" + s + "=" + rand20();
  }

  /** Fallback when you don't yet know day/agent/summaryType. */
  public static String provisional() {
    String day = LocalDate.now(ZoneId.of("Asia/Tokyo")).toString().replace("-", ""); // e.g. 20250926
    return "tmp=" + day + "=" + rand20();
  }

  private static String safe(String s) {
    if (s == null || s.isBlank()) return "_";
    // strip disallowed characters for Cosmos id
    return s.replaceAll("[/\\\\?#%]", "_").trim();
  }

  private static String base32(byte[] data) {
    StringBuilder out = new StringBuilder((data.length * 8 + 4) / 5);
    int buffer = 0, bits = 0;
    for (byte b : data) {
      buffer = (buffer << 8) | (b & 0xFF);
      bits += 8;
      while (bits >= 5) {
        int idx = (buffer >>> (bits - 5)) & 0x1F;
        out.append(B32[idx]);
        bits -= 5;
      }
    }
    if (bits > 0) out.append(B32[(buffer << (5 - bits)) & 0x1F]);
    return out.toString();
  }

  private CorrelationIds() {}
}

How to use

// In SBNotificationQueueTrigger (when you know all fields):
String cid = CorrelationIds.build(day, agentId, summaryType);

// If you don't know them yet (early stage):
String cid = CorrelationIds.provisional();

// Pass `cid` to Notification API; both services write to the same report row.

Why this works
	•	Stable prefix lets you eyeball/group records.
	•	Random 100 bits keeps IDs short but essentially collision-free.
	•	Safe charset: letters+digits+“=”; Cosmos DB document id accepts this, and it’s copy/paste friendly.


